s many unpublished images of the Beatles, Hurricanes of Color chronicles an extraordinary moment. Frankel, who was for a time a personal photographer for Jefferson Airplane and Hot Tuna, developed an innovative style—one that layered images with multiple exposures to capture the spirit of the music of the era and the experience of listening to the bands live.A must-have for fans of classic rock, this is a spectacular and profound collection of photography that complements the music of the world’s biggest performers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPhotography, Artisticy20th century. 0aPortrait photography. 0aRock musicvPictorial works. 0aRock musiciansvPortraits. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Rock.2bisacsh  aArt images.  aClassic rock.  aFillmore East.  aGrace Slick.  aHot Tuna.  aJack Casady.  aJanis Joplin.  aJefferson Airplane.  aJorma Kaukonen.  aLed Zeppelin.  aPaul McCartney.  aPink Floyd.  aRock and roll photography.  aThe Beatles.  aThe Grateful Dead.  aThe Rolling Stones.  aThe Who.  aVintage rock.  aWoodstock 1969.1 aWomack, Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271098104?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271098104423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271098104/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles